7 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 14-190.15 reads as rewritten:
8 "§ 14-190.15. Disseminating harmful material to minors; exhibiting harmful performances
9 to minors.
10 (a) Disseminating Harmful Material. – A person commits the offense of disseminating
11 harmful material to minors if, with or without consideration and knowing the character or content
12 of the material, he:the person does either of the following:
13 (1) Sells, furnishes, presents, or distributes to a minor material that is harmful to
14 minors; orminors.
15 (2) Allows a minor to review or peruse material that is harmful to minors.
16 (b) Exhibiting Harmful Performance. – A person commits the offense of exhibiting a
17 harmful performance to a minor if, with or without consideration and knowing the character or
18 content of the performance, he the person allows a minor to view a live performance that is
19 harmful to minors.
20 …
21 (e) Registration. – When a person is convicted of a violation of this section, the
22 sentencing court shall consider whether the person is a danger to the community and whether
23 requiring the person to register as a sex offender pursuant to Article 27A of this Chapter would
24 further the purposes of that Article as stated in G.S. 14-208.5. If the sentencing court rules that
25 the person is a danger to the community and that the person shall register, then an order shall be
26 entered requiring the person to register."
27 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 14-208.6(4) is amended by adding a new sub-subdivision to
28 read:
29 "g. A final conviction for a violation of G.S. 14-190.7, 14-190.8, or
30 14-190.15, only if the court sentencing the individual issues an order
31 pursuant to the applicable provision of G.S. 14-190.7, 14-190.8, or
32 14-190.15, requiring the individual to register."
33 SECTION 1.(e) Prosecutions for offenses committed before the effective date of this
34 section are not abated or affected by this section, and the statutes that would be applicable but
35 for this section remain applicable to those prosecutions.
36 SECTION 1.(f) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
37 offenses committed on or after that date.
38
39 STUDY ON HUMAN TRAFFICKING REPORTING
40 SECTION 2.(a) The General Assembly finds all of the following:
41 (1) Human trafficking is a pervasive crime that often goes undetected. National
42 statistics indicate that hundreds of thousands of people are trafficked in the
43 United States each year, yet the vast majority are never identified.
44 (2) North Carolina is recognized as a leader in efforts to combat human
45 trafficking; however, frontline professionals, including law enforcement
46 officers, healthcare providers, teachers, and social workers, often lack the
47 training, tools, and resources necessary to adequately support victim-survivors
48 and hold traffickers accountable. Services remain fragmented and limited,
49 despite a strong desire for collaboration and coordination across sectors.
50 (3) Advances in the field have produced effective models for data collection,
51 needs assessment, and landscape analysis at the State, county, and regional
Page 2 House Bill 83-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 levels. These efforts help guide statewide partners in addressing a complex
2 and constantly evolving issue.
3 SECTION 2.(b) The North Carolina Human Trafficking Commission (Commission)
4 shall conduct a study on human trafficking needs in the State, including information on the
5 development process for a statewide human trafficking reporting and response system (system).
6 After the Commission completed the study, the Commission is encouraged to begin facilitating
7 stakeholder collaboration on the development of a system that facilitates referral to the National
8 Human Trafficking hotline for crisis support as necessary. It is the intent of the General Assembly
9 to establish a system that will (i) notify law enforcement and child protection officials of high
10 priority reports, (ii) provide a secure dashboard for authorized personnel to view, triage, and
11 respond to reports, and (iii) support real-time communication between investigators and
12 survivors or reporters with consent.
13 SECTION 2.(c) This section is effective when it becomes law.
14
15 TECHNICAL CORRECTIONS
16 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 143-805(d) reads as rewritten:
17 "(d) Subsections (a) and (b) of this section shall not apply to an official or employee that
18 is engaged in any of the following activities in the course of that official's or employee's official
19 duties:
20 …
21 (8) Investigating matters involving offenders incarcerated with, or otherwise
22 under the supervision of, the Department of Adult Correction or matters
23 related to the misuse of devices owned by the Department of Adult
24 Correction."
25 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 42A-39 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
26 "(c1) Third-Party Contractor Requirements. – A third-party contractor shall ensure that any
27 employee of the third-party contractor who performs housekeeping services at the vacation rental
28 or provides check-in and check-out services for the vacation rental receive human trafficking
29 awareness training as required by subsection (c) of this section."
30 SECTION 3.(c) G.S. 130A-511(b)(1) reads as rewritten:
31 "(1) In consultation with the North Carolina Human Trafficking Commission, the
32 North Carolina Restaurant and Lodging Association, and the Department of
33 Health and Human Services, develop a training course, or identify existing
34 training courses, to inform and educate individuals about human trafficking.
35 Chapter 150B of the General Statutes does not apply to any training required
36 to be developed or identified under this subdivision."
37 SECTION 3.(d) Subsection (a) of this section is effective when it becomes law and
38 applies to investigations occurring before, on, or after that date. Subsection (b) of this section is
39 effective when it becomes law and applies to training required to be completed on or after that
40 date. Subsection (c) of this section is effective when it becomes law and applies to training
41 developed or identified before, on, or after that date.
42
43 EFFECTIVE DATE
44 SECTION 4. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
45 law.
